# 🚀 Day 32 – SSH Key-Based Authentication (Passwordless Login)

## 📌 Overview
Today I configured SSH key-based authentication to enable secure and passwordless login to a remote Linux server.

SSH keys provide stronger security compared to password-based authentication and are widely used in production environments.

---

# 🔑 1️⃣ Generate SSH Key Pair

On the client machine, generate a key pair:

```bash
ssh-keygen

It creates:

Private Key → ~/.ssh/id_rsa

Public Key → ~/.ssh/id_rsa.pub


Press Enter to accept the default file location.


---

📤 2️⃣ Copy Public Key to Remote Server

Use the following command:

ssh-copy-id username@server_ip

Example:

ssh-copy-id uday@192.168.1.20

This copies your public key to:

~/.ssh/authorized_keys on the remote server.


---

🔐 3️⃣ Login Without Password

After copying the key:

ssh username@server_ip

If configured correctly, it will not ask for a password.


---

🚫 4️⃣ Disable Password Authentication (Recommended)

Edit SSH configuration:

sudo vi /etc/ssh/sshd_config

Find and modify:

PasswordAuthentication no

Restart SSH service:

sudo systemctl restart sshd


---

📁 5️⃣ Important SSH Key Files

File	Purpose

~/.ssh/id_rsa	Private key (Keep this secure)
~/.ssh/id_rsa.pub	Public key
~/.ssh/authorized_keys	Stores allowed public keys



